[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "XXV.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 25:1-3. HUMANITY IN PUNISHMENTS.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Deuteronomy 25:1-3",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "HUMANITY IN PUNISHMENTS.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(1) They shall justify the righteous, and condemn the wicked.—“I will not justify the wicked” (Exodus 23:7). “He that justifieth the wicked, and he that condemneth the just, even they both are abomination to the Lord” (Proverbs 17:15). It should be noticed that justify is here used forensically, not meaning to make righteous, but to treat as righteous. Those who object to this sense in St. Paul’s Epistles, will find it hard to put any other sense upon the word in the rest of Holy Scripture.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "(1) ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "They shall justify the righteous, and condemn the wicked.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—“I will not justify the wicked” (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Exodus 23:7",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "). “He that justifieth the wicked, and he that condemneth the just, even they both are abomination to the Lord” (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Proverbs 17:15",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "). It should be noticed that ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "justify ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "is here used forensically, not meaning to make righteous, but to ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "treat as righteous. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "Those who object to this sense in St. Paul’s Epistles, will find it hard to put any other sense upon the word in the rest of Holy Scripture.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(2) If the wicked man be worthy to be beaten.—Literally, a son of beating, or of Haccôth, according to the Hebrew. The treatise called Maccôth, in the Talmud, describes the infliction of the punishment in later times, when “of the Jews five times” St. Paul “received forty stripes save one.” The details have been described by Canon Farrar in an appendix to his Life of St. Paul.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "(2) ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "If the wicked man be worthy to be beaten.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—Literally, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "a son of beating, or of Haccôth, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "according to the Hebrew. The treatise called ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "Maccôth, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "in the Talmud, describes the infliction of the punishment in later times, when “of the Jews five times” St. Paul “received forty stripes save one.” The details have been described by Canon Farrar in an appendix to his ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "Life of St. Paul.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Shall cause him to lie down.—The Talmud interprets the position as not sitting nor standing, nor exactly lying, but with the body inclined.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Shall cause him to lie down.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—The Talmud interprets the position as not sitting nor standing, nor exactly lying, but with the body inclined.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Before his face.—This is interpreted as on the front of his body. The thirty-nine stripes were given thirteen on one shoulder, thirteen on the other, and thirteen on the breast.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Before his face.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—This is interpreted as ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "on the front of his body. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "The thirty-nine stripes were given thirteen on one shoulder, thirteen on the other, and thirteen on the breast.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(3) Forty stripes.—The Talmud says that they considered first what a man could bear, and flogged him according to their estimate. In some cases, if the whole punishment could not be administered at once, it was divided. It is contemplated as possibly fatal, however.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "(3) ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Forty stripes.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—The Talmud says that they considered first what a man could bear, and flogged him according to their estimate. In some cases, if the whole punishment could not be administered at once, it was divided. It is contemplated as possibly fatal, however.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Lest . . . thy brother should seem vile unto thee.—The punishment was not considered to be any degradation, after it had been inflicted. It was inflicted in the synagogue, and the law was read mean while from Deuteronomy 28:58-59, with one or two other passages.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Lest . . . thy brother should seem vile unto thee.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—The punishment was not considered to be any degradation, after it had been inflicted. It was inflicted in the synagogue, and the law was read mean while from ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Deuteronomy 28:58-59",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", with one or two other passages.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(4) Thou shalt not muzzle the ox.—We have a comment on these words from St. Paul in two places (1Corinthians 9:9, and 1Timothy 5:18). It is not only written for the sake of the oxen, but to prove that the “labourer is worthy of his hire;” “they that preach the Gospel should live of the Gospel.”",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "(4) ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Thou shalt not muzzle the ox.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—We have a comment on these words from St. Paul in two places (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1Corinthians 9:9",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", and ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1Timothy 5:18",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "). It is not only written for the sake of the oxen, but to prove that the “labourer is worthy of his hire;” “they that preach the Gospel should live of the Gospel.”",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 25:1",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Deuteronomy 25:1",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "If there be a controversy between men — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Having made provision for the security of private right in some such remarkable cases as might be sufficient standards whereby to regulate all others, and having fixed punishments to the breach of the most capital laws, Moses now comes to such criminal matters as deserved only corporal penalties, and directs the inferior courts to be just and impartial in their proceedings upon all such complaints. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "They shall justify the righteous — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Acquit him from guilt and false accusations, and free him from punishment. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Condemn the wicked — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Declare him guilty, and pass sentence of condemnation upon him to suitable punishment.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "25:1-3 Every punishment should be with solemnity, that those who see it may be filled with dread, and be warned not to offend in like manner. And though the criminals must be shamed as well as put to pain, for their warning and disgrace, yet care should be taken that they do not appear totally vile. Happy those who are chastened of the Lord to humble them, that they should not be condemned with the world to destruction.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
